input:
WIBTA For bailing on Nick's friend's bachelor party? | Nick has been struggling with this one for a while and Nick needs outside opinions. 

&#x200B;

Nick has this friend (Let's call him Jake) from college, Nick and Jake have been friends going on 10 years at this point. Jake's getting married in September to a lovely girl named Jenny. They already live together (they recently bought a house together) and have been dating for 3 1/2 years. 

&#x200B;

Jenny has been very up-front with Jake about what she expects from him, from day one. She wants to start a family, eventually stop working to be a stay-at-home mom, ect. She also expects him to be more mature than he has been, ie, no all-nighters drinking, no playing video games til 4 am, things that they did during college they shouldn't be doing anymore. She's also said, many times, she explicitly is not okay with him going to strip clubs. Her exact words on the subject were, "If he went along for someone else's bachelor party, and didn't get any dances or anything, I *GUESS* I could be okay with it. But the second he's getting lap dances, I'm done."

&#x200B;

Jake's bachelor party is coming up the first weekend in August. He's already expressed his explicit desire that, regardless of what they do during the day, every night he wants to get hammered, do drugs (marijuana at the least, but he's experimented with other substances before when drunk) and go to strip clubs. He already has one picked out that "caters" to bachelor parties. They will be in a different city than the one they all live in. 

&#x200B;

Now, WIBTA if Nick bailed on being a part of all of this? Nick is one of his oldest friends, and Nick even offered to help plan the damn thing, but based on his desires to over-indulge and deliberately do things his future wife isn't okay with, Nick really doesn't want to even be there. Nick has 'grown up' a lot over the last year, and Nick has even realized that he's used Nick being a single bachelor as an excuse for doing things that upset his fiance, such as staying out drinking. He also talked Nick into going to strip clubs with him before Nick knew she wasn't okay with that happening. Nick realizes that, if one of his oldest friends bails on his bachelor party, it'll raise questions, and possibly make his fiance suspicious, which honestly, Nick would probably be okay with.   

TL;DR - Friend wants a drunk and debaucherous bachelor party with strippers, something his fiance explicitly isn't okay with, WIBTA if Nick refuses to be a part of it?

AITA for NOT answering with a definitive "NO" when Nick's girlfriend asked him "Would you ever cheat on me?" | Nick (21M) dated his ex (21F) for 3 months. Nick will describe the event that was the catalyst to their break up.

&#x200B;

It was during exam period for university. 3 days before Nick's first exam, they went on a casual date to the local mall. Nick thought it would be good to meet up and release some of their stress. They had Chinese noodles for lunch. While eating, they got talking. Nick was telling her about a YouTube video he watched the other day. It was an informative speech made by a psychologist about cheating. The psychologist explained most cheaters don't go out of their way to cheat. And when it happens, most people are surprised they're doing it themselves. It's almost unexpected. She also explained how cheating has existed for a very long time where people probably won't be able to get rid of it as a social condition. Nick felt he learned a different perspective of cheating and thought to share this to his gf at the time. Nick didn't notice anything wrong straight away. The meal continued as normal and they talked about different things as well. When they finished the meal, they paid and proceeded to browse the shops. She got progressively worse and when Nick asked her what was wrong it was like she was having an anxiety attack. She wouldn't talk to Nick for the remainder of the date and they walked out of the mall back to the car.

&#x200B;

On the way back and in the car, Nick occasionally tried to start up a conversation but she felt silent. Nick was growing more flustered and had no idea what was going on. She began by questioning Nick and asking him questions about cheating. Nick answered and was thinking through the topic as well. It's safe to say Nick has never thought about some of the questions she asked him in a proper and serious manner. Especially considering how flustered Nick became, the environment where they had this talk wasn't calm in the least. Their discussion kept on going around in a circle and it felt like she wasn't listening to Nick at all and only feeding into her own fear. She kept on brushing off everything Nick said and wasn't taking it in at all.

&#x200B;

She finally asked Nick "Would you ever cheat on me?" Part of Nick knew obviously to say "No." Even if Nick agreed or disagreed, Nick understands feelings are still important. The other half wanted to stay true to Nick and his way of thinking. Nick was thinking about what the lady said in the video and how things can just happen. Nick also didn't want to say a promise he couldn't keep. In the end Nick chose to say something along the lines of not answering with a firm no. Something like "Nick cannot promise you that". She got very sad and upset. That was the last time they ever talked in person. Nick sent a very long apology text later that night after thinking it through. Nick knew he had hurt her. However, Nick wanted to explain his side and how he couldn't betray himself and his way of thinking. Unfortunately she couldn't understand Nick's perspective. She explained how she couldn't forgive Nick for saying something like that.
